:"en-US"},{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/internship-visa-and-work-permit-differences/#webpage","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/internship-visa-and-work-permit-differences/","name":"Internship Visa and Work Permit Differences in Turkey","datePublished":"2026-03-19T10:00:00+03:00","dateModified":"2026-03-21T00:58:00+03:00","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#website"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Person","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","@id":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","caption":"Murat","inLanguage":"en-US"}},{"@type":"BlogPosting","headline":"Internship Visa and Work Permit Differences in Turkey","keywords":"Internship Visa","datePublished":"2026-03-19T10:00:00+03:00","dateModified":"2026-03-21T00:58:00+03:00","articleSection":"Visa and Immigration","author":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat"},"publisher":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"description":"What are the differences between a work visa and a work permit in Turkey? What does each permit cover, and how do you apply? Learn all the details!","name":"Internship Visa and Work Permit Differences in Turkey","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/internship-visa-and-work-permit-differences/#richSnippet","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/internship-visa-and-work-permit-differences/#webpage"},"inLanguage":"en-US","mainEntityOfPage":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/internship-visa-and-work-permit-differences/#webpage"}}]}]}', "content_html" = '<div class="toc"><span style="font-size: inherit;font-family: -apple-system, system-ui, BlinkMacSystemFont, ''Segoe UI'', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, ''Apple Color Emoji'', ''Segoe UI Emoji'', ''Segoe UI Symbol''">Turkey offers many opportunities for international students to contribute to their academic careers. One of the most important issues that foreign students should pay attention to while studying or doing post-study internships in Turkey is the difference between an internship visa and a work permit. These two documents play a crucial role in helping students achieve their career goals. However, if you are undecided about which document you should get, it is important to get the right information.</span></div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="what-is-an-internship-visa-in-turkey">What is an Internship Visa in Turkey?</h2>


<div class="wp-block-paragraph">


<p class="wp-block-paragraph">An internship visa is a special type of visa that foreign students planning to do a short-term internship in Turkey can apply for. This type of visa is only valid to participate in certain internship programs, which are usually organized in affiliation with a university, institution or company. The internship visa allows interns to reside in Turkey for the duration of their studies or internship for up to 90 days, after which the intern must leave the country. One of the most important points of the internship visa is that having this visa does not give the right to work directly. With an internship visa, interns can only do an internship in a predetermined program. If you want to work in another job or do an internship in a different institution, this is prohibited by law.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="valid-under-which-programs">Valid under which programs</h3>


<p>Internship visas are designed for students studying in specific fields and are usually valid within the framework of university internship programs. Many universities in Turkey offer internship opportunities for their students to interns from abroad. Therefore, it is important for students who wish to obtain an internship visa to contact the institutions or universities where they will be interning in advance. In addition, in order to obtain an internship visa, students are usually required to be able to show the endorsement of an educational institution and provide sufficient documentation of financial support for the expenses they will cover during the internship. Therefore, it is important to gather the necessary documents before applying and follow the application process carefully. </p></div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="what-is-a-work-permit">What is a work permit?</h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="definition-of-work-permit">Definition of Work Permit</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">A work permit is an official document that grants foreign nationals the right to work and reside legally in Turkey. This permit, issued by the&nbsp;<a href="https://www.csgb.gov.tr/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Ministry of Labor and Social Security</a></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">of the Republic of Turkey, is a document that foreigners must obtain before starting to work in Turkey. According to Law No. 6735 on International Labor Force, a person without a work permit cannot legally work in Turkey. A work permit, if the application is approved, allows the foreigner to work for a specific employer (dependent work permit) or on their own behalf (independent work permit) in Turkey. The work permit also replaces the residence permit on its own, allowing for long-term residence. In addition to the study, all the legal processes that have been granted visas must also be fully fulfilled.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="legal-basis-and-process">Legal Basis and Process</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The legal basis for obtaining a work permit is the International Labor Law No. 6735. This law states that foreigners who wish to work in Turkey must obtain a work permit. The documents required to obtain a work permit include an employment contract, permission from the employer, a diploma and identity documents. Applications are completed at the Turkish Consulates or through the online system. This process is more comprehensive compared to the internship visa application. It is of great importance for those who wish to obtain a work permit to prepare the necessary documents in full and follow the application process.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="basic-differences-between-internship-visa-and-work-permit">Basic Differences Between Internship Visa and Work Permit</h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="purpose-and-scope">Purpose and Scope</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The most obvious difference between an internship visa and a work permit is the purpose of both documents. While an internship visa aims to participate in a specific internship program, a work permit provides the legal right to work. In other words, with an internship visa you can only do an internship during your studies, while with a work permit it is possible to work in a specific job. Also, while an internship visa only allows you to do an internship in a specific organization, with a work permit you have a wider range of options regarding the position, employer and place of work. It is important to note that it is prohibited by law in Turkey to do any form of work on an internship visa.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="right-of-residence-and-work-permit">Right of Residence and Work Permit</h3>


<p>Another important difference is the right of residence. While an internship visa usually allows for a short-term residence, obtaining a work permit in Turkey also provides a long-term residence permit. This means that people who obtain a work permit also have the opportunity to extend their status. Internship visa holders are required to leave Turkey when the specified period expires. Work permits, on the other hand, can be extended as long as the employment contract continues. Therefore, you should consider your own plans before applying for an internship visa and work permit. </p></div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="other-points-to-consider">Other Points to Consider</h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="working-with-internship-visa">Working with Internship Visa</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">An internship visa is a special document designed for students who aim to participate in an internship program in Turkey, but it is not legally possible to work on the job with this visa. With an internship visa, you only have the right to take part in the designated internship program. If you intend to work in another job, this may lead to legal sanctions. It is therefore important for students planning to obtain an internship visa to familiarize themselves with the restrictions of this visa. On the other hand, those who wish to work under an internship visa cannot do so within the legal framework. If you attempt to work illegally for any reason, your visa status may be jeopardized and you may be prevented from applying for other visa types in Turkey in the future. Therefore, it is necessary to be careful.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="internship-with-work-permit">Internship with Work Permit</h3>


<p>While a work permit generally allows you to work in a full-time job, some employers may also employ interns under a work permit. However, it is critical to make a distinction here. If you want to obtain a work permit as an intern, this needs to be clearly defined. The fact that those who will do internship during the training period remain as interns is an issue that should be taken into consideration in order to prevent legal problems. For those who want to request a transition to an internship through a work permit, there is often a new application process. It is possible to obtain a work permit after the internship, depending on the legal procedures, but it should be noted that this process is not automatic. It is therefore important that you make the necessary plans for your educational process. </p></div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="internship-visa-and-work-permit-which-option-is-right-for-you">Internship Visa and Work Permit: Which Option is Right for You?</h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="tips-for-short-term-interns">Tips for short-term interns</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">An internship visa is the most suitable option for international students planning to do a short-term internship. It is sufficient to obtain this visa to participate in internship programs in Turkey, which can last up to 90 days. With this visa, you can both gain a cultural experience and gain practical knowledge that will add value to your career. However, it is very important to research the program well and keep your required documents complete throughout the visa period. If you want to experience a new culture while interning in Turkey, you will benefit from participating in social events, networking with other international students in Turkey or taking part in volunteer projects. In addition to spicing up your student years, such experiences allow you to expand your professional network.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="advice-for-those-planning-to-work-long-term">Advice for those planning to work long term</h3>


<p>Students with long-term study goals should first consider obtaining a work permit. If you want to work in a specific field with a work permit, you should clarify this with the employer you are applying to. Understanding all the terms of your employment contract will make it easier for you to apply for a work permit. If you intend to stay in Turkey for the long term and further your career here, you should also consider the possibility of extending your work permit. Earning a fixed income during your working period will also bring advantages such as participating in the social security system.</p>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="learn-the-differences-between-internship-and-work-visas">Learn the Differences Between Internship and Work Visas</h2>


<p>When choosing between both documents, you should pay attention to your planned career goals, the field in which you want to do your internship and your legal status in Turkey. While an internship visa allows you to gain experience in Turkey in a short period of time, a work permit offers significant opportunities for your long-term career plans. It is therefore crucial to gather enough information to determine which option is best for you.</p>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="frequently-asked-questions">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="does-a-work-permit-replace-a-residence-permit">Does a work permit replace a residence permit?</h3>


<p>Yes. According to Article 27 of Law No. 6735, a work permit or exemption issued in Turkey replaces a residence permit. However, this does not apply to international protection applicants and some persons with special status. You can check the <a href="https://www.csgb.gov.tr/sikca-sorulan-sorular/uluslararasi-%C4%B1sgucu-genel-mudurlugu/calisma-%C4%B1zni/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">official website</a> of the Ministry of Labor and Social Security for the necessary details.</p>


<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="can-i-get-a-residence-permit-with-an-internship-visa">Can I get a residence permit with an internship visa?</h3>


<p>No. An internship visa usually allows for a short-term stay and a separate residence permit is usually not issued. During the internship, you are only allowed to stay in Turkey for a certain period of time.</p>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Is it possible to switch to a work permit after an internship?</h3>
<p class="wp-block-heading">Yes, a work permit can be applied for after the internship ends if the legal procedures are fulfilled. However, this requires a new application; there is no automatic transition.</p>


