al-holidays-and-celebrations-in-turkiye.webp","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/guide-to-national-holidays-and-celebrations-in-turkiye.webp","width":"1168","height":"880","caption":"Anıtkabir with red and white balloons at sunset.","inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/national-holidays-in-turkey/#webpage","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/national-holidays-in-turkey/","name":"Guide to National Holidays and Celebrations in Turkey","datePublished":"2025-12-23T00:39:00+03:00","dateModified":"2026-03-15T21:48:15+03:00","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#website"},"primaryImageOfPage":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/guide-to-national-holidays-and-celebrations-in-turkiye.webp"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Person","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","@id":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","caption":"Murat","inLanguage":"en-US"}},{"@type":"BlogPosting","headline":"Guide to National Holidays and Celebrations in Turkey","keywords":"national holidays","datePublished":"2025-12-23T00:39:00+03:00","dateModified":"2026-03-15T21:48:15+03:00","articleSection":"Cultural Adaptation","author":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat"},"publisher":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"description":"Discover national holidays and celebrations in Turkey. Read now for traditions, events, and more!","name":"Guide to National Holidays and Celebrations in Turkey","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/national-holidays-in-turkey/#richSnippet","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/national-holidays-in-turkey/#webpage"},"image":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/guide-to-national-holidays-and-celebrations-in-turkiye.webp"},"inLanguage":"en-US","mainEntityOfPage":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/national-holidays-in-turkey/#webpage"}}]}]}', "content_html" = '<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Turkey, with its rich historical and cultural heritage, is a very colorful country in terms of national holidays and celebrations. These holidays are important days that reinforce social unity, remind us of the past and keep cultural values alive. In this article, we analyze the national holidays in Turkey, the ways in which these holidays are celebrated, and the importance of these holidays for international students</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="national-holidays-in-turkey-traditions-and-ways-of-celebration">Official Public Holidays in Turkey</h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">1. April 23 – National Sovereignty and Children’s Day</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">April 23, 1920, marks the opening of the Grand National Assembly of Turkey. Atatürk dedicated this day to children, who represent the future of the nation.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><strong>Traditions and Celebrations:</strong></p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>During official ceremonies, students recite poems and perform shows.</li>



<li>Children symbolically take the seats of state officials.</li>



<li>Joyful celebrations take place in schools, squares, and stadiums.</li>



<li>As part of TRT’s <em>International April 23 Children’s Festival</em>, children from various countries are invited to Turkey.</li>
</ul>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">2. May 19 – Commemoration of Atatürk, Youth and Sports Day</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">This day marks the anniversary of Atatürk’s arrival in Samsun on May 19, 1919, which initiated the Turkish War of Independence.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><strong>Traditions and Celebrations:</strong></p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
